segments.text: nurse.
Yeah, they were married and she had, I think she was about maybe two months pregnant, but this was not known.
I didn't know it when he told me.
I was shocked.
I was shocked.
I didn't know.
I was surprised.
And so was Bob Neal.
And it so happens that old PTAC
And he was one of the 16 that volunteered to stay over those extra 10 days.
And he was killed.
Oh, I see.
He was killed.
And it was either 16 of us for 10 days or 10 of us for 16 days.
I forget which.
At any rate, he was one of the eight pilots I told you originally about that was killed in combat, actually killed in the entire AVG history.
Anyway, she was pregnant, and they sort of wanted us to look after her.
Well, Red sort of took care of me in a hospital, you know, and bathed me when I was, you know, had come back and shot down and all that.
So I had developed a close rapport with her.
And my first reaction, of course, to Bob Neal, too, was the rapport with her.
We just loved those nurses.
And, you know, there were only two females with her.
And...
We said, sure.
But I said, you know, we don't know how we're going to get home.
We're going down to India.
And I told him I'm going to try my best to pull strings in the 10th Air Force Headquarters of New Delhi to get air transportation back home.
I don't know.
I'm not even going home on a slow boat.
I'm not afraid about submarines, but I just don't want to do that.
So he said, yeah.
So he told Red.
And we three had come in then, got on an airplane, provided by the old man.
got us to CNAC, Chinese National Airways Corporation, which was really the Chinese airline.
And he was boss of that, too.
So that got us to Calcutta.
So Calcutta, we were on our own from then on.
And we three stayed together all the way home.
To make a long story short- How'd you get home?
I knew General Caldwell, Colonel Caldwell at that time.
And Colonel, I had to refer to my diary notes, he later became a four-star general in the Air Force and personnel.
And General Nagel, who was commander, brigadier general in the United States Army Air Corps, 10th Air Force with headquarters in New Delhi.
General Peabody, General Peabody.
I knew all of these guys from Langley Field, the early current.
They knew me.
And of course, word got back, you know, word from the heroes.
They followed very closely.
I figured I'd call and work through Charlie Caldwell first, and I told him what the story was, and God bless him, he was just...
He was tremendous.
I think he was in the operations section.
Let's correct this.
General Naiden, N-A-I-D-E-N, was the commander of the 10th Air Force.
General Peabody is the guy that sent me to Russia later on.
But General Naiden was the commander in charge of Caldwell.
So I explained to him, and I used red.

Petak's condition is one of the reasons I said, I explained she's pregnant, and I said, quite frankly, I said, if you'd get her home on an airplane by ATC Air Transportation Command, which was under the United States Air Force, really took over Pan Am and all the airlines, you know what I mean.
I said, really, just get her home.
That's all right.
Then Bob and I, if you can't get us on, well, okay, we'll go by ship or something.
Well, he said, oh, no, no.
I said, I'll tell you what, let me do some talking, and I'll call you back.
The next day he called back and said, say, you come on up here to New Delhi.
So we got on a train up New Delhi, and I introduced Red and Bob Neal to him, and they took us to dinner, and we talked at length.
And this other gentleman, a great guy, I think of his name in a minute.
Finally, they got me an audience for General Nadin, the commander.
And I went in personally and by myself and told him the situation.
He picked up the telephone and called General Hap Arnold's office in Washington, D.C. and explained the situation to him.
And I think it was General Cuter or one of General Arnold's top aides who answered the phone and said, we'll get back with you tomorrow and give you the answer.
And that morning, General Layton called me in the office and he handed me a wire and he said,
He said, send him a wire.
He had a wire in his hand.
Give Quadrant Leader Charles R. Bond, Bob Neal, and Nurse Red P-Tech of the American Flying Interior Group a full accord and courtesy of the Air Transport Command back to the United States.
And from then on, you know, no problem.
So they flew you by?
Yeah, and we got on ATC airplanes, various types.
Actually, we flew in an old goonie bird from New Delhi clear across India to Karachi.
Karachi, we flew across to Allahabad, and Allahabad to Aden, Aden to Khartoum, Khartoum to Tano,
What do you call it, not the same name now, what is it?
Gold Coast.
Gold Coast.
That's from the Gold Coast to Trans-Pertuson, an old, the only commercial version of the B-17 that ever built one of them.
TWA.
But as I mentioned, we flew from there to Natal, Natal then on this way back to Miami.
Did you have a stunt there?
Well, that's on the way over.
Oh, okay.
and back up to Miami.
No, we did.
We landed sentinel with them.
That's a British air base at that time.
And then when I got back to Miami, of course, we told Red goodbye, and Bob Neal and I went to New York, and Bob had ideas, and did go with Penebroke.
a forerunner of Pan Am, eventually was taken over from Pan Am, Pan American Grace, as a pilot with an old flying boat, and he's Navy anyhow, and I was going to go to work for TWA.
But, what happened after that?
He went with Pan Am, I mean Pan Am, and flew with them a long time, and then finally he quit, and went to
back to his old love, state of Washington, and he's now running a little fishing resort and been up there ever since on a little island in the sound right north of Seattle.
And living with his wife.
So he stayed with Pan Am for the rest of his career?
No, no, he resigned from Pan Am.
He resigned after about four or five years.
Maybe six or eight years.
And Red Petak is currently married to a gentleman who is running a, some sort of fish wholesale business in, I think it's Maryland, someplace in Maryland.
And what did you decide to do?
Well, my objective was to get a rate commission in the Air Force, and I didn't give up.
So, I...
I went with Bob Neal up and talked to Panagra people, and I wasn't too impressed with those people, but I still wanted commission in the Air Force.
They wanted to go in commercial airlines.
I wanted my regular commission, so I went down to Dallas Civilian.
Had plenty of money at that time.
I went down to Washington and walked into the munition building and kept talking to people until I got to General Hap Arnold's office and told him who I was.
And of course, the officers, the major officers, they had certainly heard of Flying Tigers, and a lot of them had heard of me.
I was one of the so-called heroes.
And next thing I know, I finally got to General Cuter's office.
K-U-T-E-R.
He was a very good gentleman.
He suddenly became a four-star general.
Very fine.
He was brilliant also.
Got a half-armed right-hand man.
And I walked into his office and I was, I was aggressive.
I had one objective in mind and I didn't waste any time.
I didn't pull any punches.
And I said, I have come to see General Arnold, first of all.
I'm sure he bought and he knew I was one.
He's the one, by the way, who got us here.
He said, well, General Arnott is going to be busy for a long time.
I said, General Cuter, I know he's very busy, but I came here to see him.
If I can't see him, then let's say so and I'll leave.
He said, oh, no, wait a minute.
Don't get mad.
I said, you came here to see him, didn't you?
I said, that's right.
He said, well, don't leave until you see him.
I said, well, I'm not going to wait all week.
He said, I think we can probably get an appointment in the morning.
I said, all right then, I'll wait until tomorrow.
I hope he shook hands, and I walked down.
Sure, if he called me 9 o'clock the next morning, I'd call him at 10, something like that.
And I came down, and at the appropriate time, whenever it was, General Kuehler took me in General Arnold's office, and there he was sitting by his desk with his blouse open the way he usually does.
And terrific man, terrific man.
But I bet he had at least...
six or eight generals crowding around him, standing at the desk.
And it became fairly obvious, very obvious in no short, in a very short period of time, what all of the generals were doing.
And... What were they doing?
I'll tell you.
I was, I'm going too slow for you, I know I'm dragging you out, but I, I took hands with the general, I said, told him where I was, and he says, what can I do for you?
I said, General Arnold, I want a regular commission in the Air Force.
I said, that's all I want.
I said, I'll go back to China right now.
I would have stayed in China, and I told Tex Sanders I'd stay in China if you'd give me a regular commission.
I had a long talk with General Berg.
He said he'd take Congress and give me a regular commission.
I said, if anybody can give me a regular commission, I believe you can.
I said, that's what I want.
And then I'm back in the Air Force.
I love it.
He said, well...
He says, Burton was right, that it will take an act of Congress, and I just don't see how I can do it.
But tell me, young man, now tell me, what is it about the P-40 that you guys love and did so well?
And he changed the conversation completely.
And then he dominated me from then on, you know.
And he got me started, and that's what all these journalists...
They wanted to hear it.
General Arnold was in a very bad political situation.
He was being pushed by Congress and everybody that his superior's ego was such a fantastic airplane.
He'd been shooting everything out of the sky, you know.
He'd just eaten up American airplanes in the Philippines.
You know, Pearl Harbor, fantastic airplane.
And here, the Flying Tigers just shoot them down out of the sky like they're nothing.
Why can't, what's the matter with you people in the Air Force?
General Arnold was really in the spot.
Here was an expert back.
You know, been flying, had two, practically double A's.
So he wants them the harshest amount.
So he asked, and so I just built my guts right there, and I stood up and just let them have it like I'm telling you right now.
And I said, there's not a damn thing wrong with the P-40.
I said, people don't know how to fight.
I said, there's a certain way you've got to fight it.
Boy, these gentlemen stand there with their mouths open.
And
I said, it's a matter of tactics.
I said, in some ways, the Japanese zero is superior to our airplane.
But I said, in other ways, it won't match it.
And then I explained the whole situation.
What did you say?
Well, the P-40 is structurally, we always build a terrific airplane.
The P-40 structurally was far superior to the zero.
The zero was a tin can compared to a heavy steel, if you will, airplane.
We could out-dive it.
but we could not out-turn it.
The top speed of them were about equal.
At altitude, the jet airplane, around 20,000 feet to zero, was probably superior to the P-40.
At any altitude, it would out-turn the P-40, easily, out-climb it, out-maneuver it.
You just could not maneuver it.
But the P-40, you could put it straight down a dive and never worry about the tail coming off.
It'd get cockeyed on you because of the propeller.
Turk torsion, but it would leave the Zero away and he couldn't, his terminal speed was, you know, slower than if he'd fought him.
Pretty soon he was out of gunnery range.
All he had to do was dive away, go out and climb back up and use a tactic that Chennault told us.
And that's the way we took care of the Zero.
And that's what you told Half Iron?
Yeah, and I told the story and it, you know, I summarized things.
Strictly tactics.
And I said, there's nothing in the world wrong with the Peacock.
I'd go back and water it right now.
And, oh boy, he took a death tear.
Well, I made friends with the old man, obviously.
But, again, he was sorry, and I left very, very, very sad.
Oh, what did the other eight generals that were standing around say?
Oh, they just listened.
They didn't say anything?
No.
Oh, a few, they'd come up and answer a few questions.
Well, you know, what's your, what's the max speed you think of the Zero?
What do you think of the Jap pilot?
Those types of questions.
It'd be typical.
And what'd you answer to the Japanese pilot question?
Well, the Japanese pilot was a, in my opinion, was a mechanical type guy.
He didn't have the, this is one that I met in combat.
Why they flew their formation the way they did, which was absolutely asinine, I'll never know, like a play hive on airplanes.
They stuck to 18,000 feet.
Their tactics were stereotyped.
We knew exactly what they were going to do each time they came over.
They didn't bury them.
The Navy pilot was far superior to the Army pilot, definitely.
Far superior.
That's the reason they bring them into hand-counted fine campaign.
They're going to eliminate us.
Had we fought zeroes all the time,
Initially, I didn't start.
I think we would have had a little bit tougher time.
Sure.
I still think we would have prevailed.
The primary question was oriented to the P-40 versus the Zero, and that's what the old man was.
In other words, they were trying to get the old man to buy everything like a Zero.
Well, he, General Oren, wasn't for it, and his generals weren't for it, but they needed backup.
Yeah.
They wanted an expert's opinion on this, and then take it to Congress.
And look what came out of the P-40, the P-51, one of the greatest airplanes we ever built.
Mustang, you know?
Yeah.
And then the old iron-gutted jug, we called it, the P-47, you know, that great big thing.
It had the, when you turn that thing into a power dive, you never worry about it coming to pieces.
Run through an orange grove on a landing, you know, belly up, it never hurts you.
And so, how long were you with General Arno?
I wasn't in there long in about 45 minutes.
Thank you.
Turned around and left.
Went back.
Then I went home.
Do you know what the date of this meeting was?
That's not my diary.
My diary ended when I landed in Miami.
August the 17th.
It must have been the latter part of August.
I can't
I don't remember, and I don't think I'm recording.
Last of August, 1942.
Last of August, 1942.
Okay.
And subsequent to that, then, see, I was disappointed, and I had failed in one of my missions.
I had made enough money to come back and buy a house for my mom and dad.
I did that.
How much money did you make?
Oh, I came back with more than $10,000 in my bank.
Wow.
With more than $15,000.
More than $15,000?
Boy, that's a lot of money for them, isn't it?
Yeah.
And none of that was gambling.
I didn't gamble.
No, that was just combat pay.
Combat pay and travel pay, extra pay for staying over longer, and transportation pay, some transportation expense pay that I didn't use.
But at any rate, I achieved two of my objectives.
I got the combat experience.
Yeah.
I have my mother and father put them in a home, which is better than they've been used to, which I felt great about.
But third one, I didn't get the regular permission.
But I still had my blood.
You still had your what?
I had it in my blood, the military.
I started to work for TWA and worked for about 16 days and decided it wasn't for me and walked in and told Jack Person, the personnel manager,
In the gravity point hangar there at National Air Force.
Look, I'm sorry.
I just, I don't have it in me.
I've got to go back to the Air Force.
And he took one look at me and says, I understand perfectly.
I don't blame you a bit.
He said, you can go right ahead.
He said, furthermore, we'll pay you for the 16 days that you've just been taking a physical examination for us.
He says, I'm proud of you.
So I walked across to
Were you flying during that time?
No, I was just being, for TWA?
No, I was just, 16 days, filling out forms and taking a physical exam.
They gave me a complete physical.
Okay, so then you went back to... At that time, I don't, I have, I'm not sure whether it was in the Pentagon, but then whether it was finished or not.
It seemed like I went over to the Pentagon.
I went back in the Air Force, or wherever it was.
The personnel told them I'm going to go back to service.
Of course, they immediately took me back in and put me in.
As a reserve officer?
As a reserve officer, second lieutenant.
Second lieutenant?
When you could have been a major?
Well, legally, I had to go back that way.
They explained to me that this is, when I went back home and told them I wanted to go back to service, this is the way they told me.
Well, I said,
Yeah, we'll take you in as a first lieutenant.
We have to do this reserve.
I think it's October the 14th, 1942.
Okay.
And that's when my active duty started again.
Okay.
And then in one week, they promoted me to a captain.
Another week, I was promoted to a major.
Another week, I was promoted to a lieutenant colonel.
I stayed there about two or three months in the Pentagon.
Of course, in the meantime, I'd come back to Dallas in August and got married to Dorn on the 14th of August, 19.
Okay, before we get into this part of your career, which starts October 1942, there are a couple of questions, just a couple more questions I want to ask about the Flying Tigers.
One, you landed a lot of RAF bases, Royal Air Force bases.
And I was wondering about the relationship between the British maintenance men, the base captains, the fliers, and the American Flying Tigers.
How'd you get along with them?
Well, tremendous.
Matter of fact, one RAF pilot, no, he was an administrative officer, he actually left the RAF in Rangoon
And in effect, just told him to go to hell.
He went up into Kunming, China with us and stayed with us until we disbanded.
And I don't know what ever happened to that man, but he never, as far as I know, he never went back to the RAF.
Eventually, I sort of lost track of him.
I think his name was Davis.
I don't know what happened to him.
Why did he do that?
He wasn't getting the job back?
He loved us.
He loved us.
He wanted to stay with us.
He thought we were without a doubt the best.
He thought we were gods, superhumans.
He thought we were the greatest outfit in the world.
The RAF pilots that I met, most of them, the majority of them by far, I had a great respect for.
I never will forget old William Commander Carey, a terrific guy.
He thought the world and all of us.
You know, we were the only ones.
that were really making any progress or could, you know, just knock the Japs off at will.
We were the only bright spot in the entire world against the Japanese Air Force.
Against Japan.
Yeah.
And until, you know, Doolittle, Major Ray, and incidentally Doolittle folks came back.
We met several of them coming back to China with us.
Oh, wow.
You had to tell me about that.
I talked to several of them.
But we were the only bright spot on the horizon then.
The old...
And so the few of the bomber pilots I didn't particularly care about.
I had a lot of service with the RAF in subsequent times, you know.
And did they go out on you?
Oh boy, they'd go in their hurricane just like we would, and eager to go as we were.
And that hurricane was a sorry, it was a sorry airplane, the P-40.
And they lost a lot of people because they didn't have the benefit of our tactics and Chenault's construction.
They lost
they just lost practically everything in Singapore and wherever they were.
They lost a lot of people.

But the, no telling how many missions Carrie had, Wing Commander Carrie had been on, and he'd get, Bob Neal was one of his favorites, they came very close, and of course I'd already known Bob, and we'd get together at night and get on the drinking spree sometime.
Terrific guy.
We got along great together.
So they shared
Are you, whenever you, when you were over there, you shared food and supplies?
They actually, outside of China, if it wasn't for the RAF and their support, we couldn't have gotten home.
We depend on them.
And apparently the Chinese who lent leaves in the United States and Britain had come to this agreement that in Burma, you know, they'd support us as well.
And that's the reason we used their air bases.
And we would go down to send General Chenault's airplane down to Singapore before it was taken to get some maybe tires from them.
We'd be out of tires, you know.
The tires for their particular airplanes, that's how I think it flew to Buffalo with 50 people on it.
We used their oxygen.
We used their mess facilities.
We got along great with them.
The airmen.
particularly got along greatly.
The airmen got along much, much better with them than they did with the United States Air Force types that began to come over there.
Why?
Oh, well, the airmen were the NCOs, particularly the key ones.
Not only the Air Force, but the Navy, Marines, and Air Force.
All of them, they had more of a reason, I think, to get out of the services maybe than
The officers, they were more griped, I think, at the service.
So you had a chance to make more money.
And we had some Mavericks in the, many more Maverick types in the so-called enlisted types, airmen, than we did in the Air Force.
We had a few 8-ball, I mean in the pilots.
We had a few 8-ball officer types in the pilots.
Now, competence, I'm not telling them competence.
These airmen were fantastic.
They were terrific.
But some of them did carry a chip on their shoulder.
Against the Army Air Force.
Well, Navy, too, and Marine.

Whenever they'd catch a, you know, during the days when ATC began to ferry supplies up into China, you know, a lot of parts of our one year, April up through July, we'd meet some of the Air Force officers.
Particularly the higher ranking ones, colonels and brigadier general types, you know.
The airmen get a few drinks in there, run to their bell, and they were, they didn't sober.
Oh, really?
And I, of course, I didn't like to see that.
I felt a little ashamed of that.
But, you know, in some cases, maybe they had a reason, because, well, I don't know.

It was my observation that generally the Air Force types, Navy types, and what few Marine Corps types, you know, that came over there that were real gentlemen and knew what they were doing and knew the situation, they didn't have trouble.
But Prince Tex Handler had the wrong idea when he tried to recruit them.
Oh, yeah.
Now, here's a question about the airmen.
What?
Here's a question about the airmen.
When Chennault changed or was back in, I guess, commission back in the Air Force, what happened to the airmen?
Well, the airmen came home, too.
Oh, they did, huh?
See, of course, now you say when they come home, they were subject to induction and prescription and, I'm sure, come back to service.
I can't remember exactly how many.
You were too, weren't you?
Right.
Technically?
Right.
But see, had I gone to work for airlines, they wouldn't pay.
See, that would be a, what do you call it, exempted job.
Well, the airmen came back and sought the same types of jobs, like with the aircraft industry, with airlines.
A lot of them went with airlines.
Many of them went with airlines.
And, you know, the pilots, like crew chiefs, take a crew chief and they'd talk.
They put in there two bits for crew teeth to go to work for there, and the airlines needed them.
Sure.
Did Chennault try to talk them into staying?
He treated them the same way he did the politics.
He said, I can sure use you, but you do, you've earned it.
You do what you want to do.
If you want to go home, I don't know where to get you.
And most of them went home, too.
Yeah.
And most of them had to go by boat.
It took them a long time to get home.
What happened to the others?
Out of your entire Flying Tiger group in July, at the end, how many were there left, and how many decided to stay with Chenault, and how many decided to go home?
At the date of disbandment on July 4th, actually,
July the 20th, 16 days after, you know, he had some of us stay out.
Let's say on the 20th of July, all of us went home except, if I remember correctly, I think there were five or six pilots, five or six Air Force pilots that decided to stay over.
Well, no, Tex Hill was like the Navy.
Five or six pilots decided to stay over and go into the Air Force, right on the spot.
And Airman, I don't really recall, and I'm not even sure it's in my diary book there, or in my diary.
So five or six pilots out of how many?
I'd say out of... That were left on the 4th of July.
I'm guessing, I'd say four or five out of about, at that time,
40, 45, see a lot of them had already gone home.
Some of the pilots went home just before July 4th.
They just had it.
Well, they had it, yeah, and they knew they were good.
And the old man people, they were in Kunming not doing a thing.
He didn't actually have enough airplanes for him to fly.
Oh, no kidding.
Or enough anything for the airmen to do.
Kunming was rapidly becoming nothing but a sort of a
air transport stopped.
The Japanese weren't raising a place anymore.
So by May of 42, the Flying Tigers were beginning to disband.
I'd say as early as June.
Maybe late May, yeah.
Okay, okay.
And your original, what did you say you had?
My original plan was to have 100 airplanes and 100 pilots, and a total of 250 people.
And how many did you ever have full-strength, do you think?
No, we never did have full-strength pilots.
No, I know, but approximately how many did you ever have?
I think probably 65.
The last contingent was about the same as mine, around 35.
Maybe 70.
Okay, and all...
but five decided to go, four or five decided to go home.
Yeah.
Now, did you find that unusual?
That all, that no one wanted to stay and continue the war effort?
No, I didn't.
As a matter of fact, Tex Hill was ex-Navy.
Tex was actually born in China.
His missionary parents.
He's a Texan boy.
You've probably heard of him.
He stayed over.
Bill Martin, a Texacana boy.
No, he went back over.
Mack McCormick?
I forget his name.
I can't remember his name.
He was an Air Force fighter jockey.
I think...
I don't know.
It's hard.
I've asked myself that question.
Why did they stay?
Tex Hill is a
He's an Orient.
He loves the Orient.
Like I say, he was born and raised over there.
As a matter of fact, Tex still represents certain agencies in the Far East today.
He spent a lot of time in Taiwan, Japan, and the Far East.
But the other guys, as a matter of fact, two out of those five I think were killed
I don't know.
Everybody was just eager to get home now.
Oh yeah, by far a majority.
Were you sort of sad?
Tired, combat weary.
I think really, in my opinion, I'm convinced that
Texas Amherst's approach to recruit us was by far the greatest factor for his policy.
And I know had the Air Force, you know it still hasn't come around, I think 47 they did something, the act of 47 on the defense department, that's when I got my regular commission, 1947.
So I ultimately achieved that too.
But I had the Air Force, you know,
said, well, look, we'll get an acronym where we can give.
You guys have earned it in your combat duty.
Although you left the service, we'll get you ready.
I think, I bet you there could have been as many as 25 or 30, let's say.
I would say 25 or 30.
And a lot of the airmen, I think, see,
You know, an airman becomes close camaraderie between a lot of the airmen and the pilots over there.
We're a pilot state.
I'm sure you can talk to airmen in the state.
A lot of them in the state.
But just like anything, it's like fire.
It starts spreading.
It keeps spreading like more and more.
As the river gets around, I'm going home.
Gee, if you go home, I'll go home.
Something like that.
Sure.
Chain effect.
Okay.
Okay.
Now, tell me about Doolittle.
All I know about the Doolittle is, of course, we heard about it on the radio.
Was it July of 42?
June of 42?
It had to be early in July.
Was it April?
Maybe it was April.
April, I think.
Because, matter of fact, we were still at Kunming when I met two of the pilots
At the hostel one night, they had trickled down through the underground.
I mean, Chinese picked them up, got them through the line.
Some of them went down the line.
A lot of them went down the line.
Japanese line.
Chinese bugged them through the line.
Basically, going down to Kunming, where air transport command terminal is, before they get on.
And I met a couple of them there.
I'm pretty sure it was around April.
